### Run the Bubble Tea Application (Go)

Source: https://github.com/charmbracelet/bubbletea/blob/main/tutorials/basics/README.md

This code snippet shows how to initialize and run a Bubble Tea application. It creates a new program with an initial model and executes it, handling any potential errors during runtime. This is the main entry point for a Bubble Tea application.

```go
func main() {
    p := tea.NewProgram(initialModel())
    if _, err := p.Run(); err != nil {
        fmt.Printf("Alas, there's been an error: %v", err)
        os.Exit(1)
    }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Control Bubble Tea Program Execution (Go)

Source: https://context7.com/charmbracelet/bubbletea/llms.txt

This Go code illustrates how to control a running Bubble Tea program externally using methods like Send, Quit, and Wait. It demonstrates sending messages to the program, initiating a graceful shutdown, and blocking until the program finishes. Requires the 'time' package.

```go
package main

import (
    "time"

    tea "github.com/charmbracelet/bubbletea"
)

type externalMsg string

func main() {
    p := tea.NewProgram(model{})

    // Run program in goroutine
    go func() {
        p.Run()
    }()

    // Send messages from outside
    time.Sleep(2 * time.Second)
    p.Send(externalMsg("Hello from outside!"))

    // Graceful quit
    time.Sleep(2 * time.Second)
    p.Quit()

    // Or immediate termination
    // p.Kill()

    // Wait for program to finish
    p.Wait()
}

// Print above the TUI (persistent output)
func printStatus(p *tea.Program) {
    p.Println("Status update: all systems go")
    p.Printf("Time: %s", time.Now().Format(time.RFC3339))
}
```

--------------------------------

### Bubble Tea Program Initialization and Execution in Go

Source: https://context7.com/charmbracelet/bubbletea/llms.txt

Shows how to create a new Bubble Tea program instance using `tea.NewProgram` and execute its event loop with `p.Run()`. This example includes optional program configurations like using the alternate screen buffer and enabling mouse support.

```go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "log"

    tea "github.com/charmbracelet/bubbletea"
)

type model struct {
    message string
}

func (m model) Init() tea.Cmd { return nil }

func (m model) Update(msg tea.Msg) (tea.Model, tea.Cmd) {
    switch msg := msg.(type) {
    case tea.KeyMsg:
        if msg.String() == "q" {
            return m, tea.Quit
        }
    }
    return m, nil
}

func (m model) View() string {
    return m.message + "\nPress q to quit."
}

func main() {
    // Create program with options
    p := tea.NewProgram(
        model{message: "Hello, Bubble Tea!"},
        tea.WithAltScreen(),           // Use alternate screen buffer
        tea.WithMouseCellMotion(),     // Enable mouse support
    )

    // Run returns final model and any error
    finalModel, err := p.Run()
    if err != nil {
        log.Fatal(err)
    }

    fmt.Printf("Final state: %+v\n", finalModel)
}
```

### Bubble Tea Documentation > Program Methods - Send, Quit, Kill, Wait

Source: https://context7.com/charmbracelet/bubbletea/llms.txt

Bubble Tea programs can be controlled from outside using several methods: `Send` allows you to inject messages into the running program, `Quit` initiates a graceful shutdown, `Kill` terminates the program immediately, and `Wait` blocks until the program has finished execution. These methods are invaluable for orchestrating application lifecycles, testing, or integrating Bubble Tea applications with other Go processes.

--------------------------------

### Bubble Tea Tutorial > All Together Now

Source: https://github.com/charmbracelet/bubbletea/blob/main/README.md

To run a Bubble Tea application, you initialize it with `tea.NewProgram`, passing in the initial model. The `p.Run()` method then starts the Bubble Tea runtime, which manages the application's lifecycle, event loop, and rendering. Error handling is crucial, so it's recommended to check the error returned by `p.Run()` and exit gracefully if any issues occur.

